## Compute services in AWS
   - Compute: servers, CPUs for computing, distributed in EC2 instances (Elastic Compute Cloud)
        - EC2 are virtual machines that emulate physical hardware
        - Pay even if there is not code running in the instance, as long as the instance is not in "stopped" state
        - Types of instances: storage, computing or memory optimized, accelerated computing
        - Better for long running applications
        - Granular control, as in physical
   - Containers services: 
        - EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service). Orchestrate containairez applications with Kubernetes
        - ECS (Elastic Container Service)
        - Fargate: Run container apps serverless 
        - Good for fast deploy, can start and top quickly
        - Containers can isolate applications and run microservices to make them independent
        - Containers can be as small or as large as needed
        - If persistent data is required or complex networking configurations, container are not so portable
   - Serverless
        - lambda function: allow to run code without having to manage servers
        - only pay when the function is running
        - Apps running < 15 mins
        - Good when AWS services call other AWS services.
        - AWS Step functions: sequential execution of several functions.

AWS Batch: - efficiently run hundreds of thousands of batch computing jobs on AWS.
           - Using Fargate. 
           - Finite duration jobs that don't require interaction. 
           - Start when resources available. They go into the queue. Similar to HPC

Amazon Elastic Beanstalk:
    - When you deploy an app, Beanstalk automatically provisions and manages:
         Amazon EC2 (servers)
         Amazon Elastic Load Balancer (traffic distribution)
         Amazon Auto Scaling (scale up/down instances)
         Monitoring via CloudWatch
         Networking (VPC setup, security groups)

AWS LightSail:
    - pre-packaged virtual servers with predictable pricing and simple setup
    - "easy" mode of EC2. pre-configured EC2


Vertical Scaling: increase size of instance, needs to reboot.
Horizontal scaling: add more small instances. Cheaper.


Design principles AWS:
   - Operational excellence
   - Security
   - Relibaility
   - Operational efficiency
